  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is macro in MS Excel?",
  "response": "In Microsoft Excel, a **macro** is a sequence of instructions or commands that automate repetitive tasks. Macros are written in **VBA (Visual Basic for Applications)**, a programming language integrated into Excel. They allow you to record or write code to perform specific actions, such as formatting data, performing calculations, or generating reports.\n\n### Key Features of Macros:\n1. **Automation**: Macros can automate repetitive tasks, saving time and reducing errors.\n2. **Customization**: You can create macros to perform specific actions tailored to your needs.\n3. **Recording**: Excel allows you to record macros by performing tasks manually, which are then converted into VBA code.\n4. **Programming**: Advanced users can write and edit VBA code to create more complex macros.\n5. **Reusability**: Once created, macros can be run multiple times or applied to different datasets.\n\n### Uses of Macros in Excel:\n- Formatting large datasets.\n- Importing and exporting data.\n- Generating reports automatically.\n- Performing complex calculations.\n- Creating custom functions or tools.\n\n### How to Create a Macro:\n1. **Record a Macro**:\n   - Go to the **Developer** tab (if not visible, enable it in Excel Options).\n   - Click **Record Macro**.\n   - Perform the tasks you want to automate.\n   - Click **Stop Recording**.\n   - The recorded actions are saved as VBA code.\n\n2. **Write a Macro**:\n   - Open the **VBA Editor** (Alt + F11).\n   - Write or edit VBA code in the editor.\n   - Save and run the macro.\n\n### Running a Macro:\n- Go to the **Developer** tab.\n- Click **Macros**, select the macro, and click **Run**.\n- Assign a macro to a button, keyboard shortcut, or ribbon for quick access.\n\n### Security:\n- Macros can contain malicious code, so Excel disables them by default.\n- Enable macros only from trusted sources in **File > Options > Trust Center > Trust Center Settings > Macro Settings**.\n\nMacros are a powerful tool in Excel for improving efficiency and productivity, especially when dealing with large or complex datasets.",
